data.name: InterpolationDescription_Akima
data.value:
The Akima interpolation is a continuously differentiable sub-spline interpolation. It is built from piecewise third order polynomials. Only data from the next neighbor points is used to determine the coefficients of the interpolation polynomial. There is no need to solve large equation systems and therefore this interpolation method is computationally very efficient. Because no functional form for the whole curve is assumed and only a small number of points is taken into account this method does not lead to unnatural wiggles in the resulting curve. The monotonicity of the specified data points is not necessarily retained by the resulting interpolation function. By additional constraints on the estimated derivatives a monotonicity preserving interpolation function can be constructed.
H. Akima, ``A New Method of Interpolation and Smooth Curve Fitting Based on Local Procedures,'' J.ACM, vol. 17, no. 4, pp. 589-602, 1970.
http://www.iue.tuwien.ac.at/phd/rottinger/node60.html

data.name: GPUProcessing_INFO
data.value:
----- INFO ----- Please read these instructions carefully!
SpectraFox supports parallelization through GPU computing for some processors and graphic cards. On the left all compatible GPUs are listed. Below you can select you default GPU and processing mode. If no compatible GPU is found, be sure to have installed the latest driver for you graphic card, and have downloaded the appropriate GPU computing package libraries from you vendor.
Intel CPU/GPU: (OpenCL) http://software.intel.com/en-us/vcsource/tools/opencl-sdk
NVIDIA: (CUDA/OpenCL) https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-downloads
AMD/ATI: (OpenCL) http://developer.amd.com/tools-and-sdks/heterogeneous-computing/amd-accelerated-parallel-processing-app-sdk/downloads/
!!! Be aware for NVIDIA's CUDA: If monitors are attached to the graphic card, Windows will reset your display driver, and the calculation will abort, if the calculations are too time consuming. Use OpenCL instead!!!
If the initialization of GPU computing fails, SpectraFox will always fall back to the CPU version of the code.
